You will see that it‚Äôs not doing what you intended.  The `+` operator works left-to-right, so no mathematical addition is taking place.  You can easily fix it with parentheses:

    InputStream is = getClass().getResourceAsStream(&quot;/res/moon/&quot; + (i + 1) + &quot;.png&quot;);
    //              math is performed before string concatenation  ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë

If you look at the documentation for [the methods of ImageIO](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.desktop/javax/imageio/ImageIO.html#method-summary), you will see there is a read(URL) method.  This is much easier to use when loading resources:

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; IMAGE_COUNT; i++) {
        URL imageLocation = getClass().getResource(&quot;/res/moon/&quot; + (i + 1) + &quot;.png&quot;);
        moonIdle[i] = ImageIO.read(imageLocation);
    }

No need to worry about closing an InputStream.  (Notice the use of getResource instead of getResourceAsStream.)

Instead of ignoring an IOException for each image, place the entire loop inside one try/catch.  If you can‚Äôt load an image, you certainly don‚Äôt want to keep going as if nothing‚Äôs wrong.

    try {
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; IMAGE_COUNT; i++) {
            URL imageLocation = getClass().getResource(&quot;/res/moon/&quot; + (i + 1) + &quot;.png&quot;);
            moonIdle[i] = ImageIO.read(imageLocation);
        }
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }

Finally, I assume your application will not work properly without those images loaded, since there won‚Äôt be much for a user to see.  Instead of ignoring an IOException, treat it as a fatal error.

    try {
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; IMAGE_COUNT; i++) {
            String resourcePath = &quot;/res/moon/&quot; + (i + 1) + &quot;.png&quot;;

            URL imageLocation = getClass().getResource(resourcePath);

            if (imageLocation == null) {
                throw new RuntimeException(
                    &quot;Missing image in application: &quot;
                    + &quot;\&quot;&quot; + resourcePath + &quot;\&quot;&quot;);
            }

            moonIdle[i] = ImageIO.read(imageLocation);

            if (moonIdle[i] == null) {
                throw new RuntimeException(
                    &quot;Invalid image in application at &quot; + imageLocation);
            }
        }
    } catch (IOException e) {
        throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Cannot load internal image!&quot;, e);
    }

Notice that the above code does not just call printStackTrace in its catch block and keep going as if nothing‚Äôs wrong.  That‚Äôs because something *is* wrong‚Äîseriously wrong, in fact.  The application cannot run properly without those images!  The correct course of action is to halt the program logic, which is what exceptions are designed to do.  Rarely is it a good idea to just print/log an exception and keep going as if nothing is wrong.

Also, notice that the caught exception is itself passed as an argument when constructing the RuntimeException.  This guarantees that the original exception, and its stack trace information, are not lost.  Eventually, some code at some level will print that stack trace, even if it‚Äôs Java SE itself who does so.

